My first letter to S.A.
B.E.
Burton Emmett
120 WEST 32nd STREET
New York
[There is nothing in this letter asking for, or hinting for, any favor.]
My dear Mr. Anderson
I have just finished reading in "Sherwood Anderson's Note book" your tribute to Alfred Steiglitz.
For a long time, I have wanted to write you about something else. But there is such bigness, such tremendous significance in your way of looking at things that- although any other author living would be pleased, I am sure- I have feared that you would feel unclear bothered. And so, to keep my self-respect, I haven't written you.
But about this Steiglitz thing, how I wish that I myself, for the moment, were Mr. Sherwood Anderson so that I might tell the author of that "note" how deeply it has impressed me. You could do it without adjectives or adverbs too! I am going to say it as simply as I can: the Steiglitz tribute seems to me to be the most

Burton Emmett
120 WEST 32nd STREET
New York
2
deeply felt, the most sincerely stated, the most beautifully handled and the most inspiring single thing that I have read for- I can't remember how long. The passage about the way the driving in of the nails hurt the old unclear builder is not the most inspiring part; but so far as craftsmanship in thinking and in words and crashing effectiveness are concerned, and even you yourself have done anything more wonderful.
If the Steiglitz essay had not just simply driven me to write you, I doubt if I ever would have done so. But now that I am writing you I dont seem to be so worried about you attitude toward the little subject referred to in my second paragraph- you cant do anything worse than say "Hell!" and throw this away. And so- the truth is that I am collecting everything I can get my hands on by three or four of our most recent American authors, yourself and Dreisen being the two more important. What I

Burton Emmet
120 WEST 32nd STREET
New York
3
wanted to tell you is that I am sincerely ambitious to build up, as time goes on, one of the finest Sherwood Anderson collections in America. I can almost see your sneer of contempt at so petty, tawdry an idea- but you're wrong and, if we should get acquainted some day, I can prove it. This would be one hell of a world if there had been no collectors!
My means are more than ample and I would say "the finest" instead of "one of the finest" except that I would have no chance against some wild rich man who might want to buy up all of your manuscripts as John Quinn did with Conrad's- and also except for the fact that, more and more, "modern art" paintings and prints are clamoring for a large share of my collecting money. 
As I said, I have wanted to tell you this. That is all for now. Please dont bother to acknowledge this letter- maybe some day I'll write one that deserves an answer.
Sincerely
Burton Emmett 5/2/26

MEMO from BURTON EMMETT, 120 West Thirty-Second Street, New York. Pennsylvania 6480
Mr. Anderson, you're as right as rain and I know it- but I dont believe either of us knows any? too much about right prices for manuscripts. The funny prices in enclosed Drake catalogue are enough to rattle anybody, aren't they?
I am spending all my spare time on the farm this summer and leaving collecting alone. I hope you'll be in N.Y. this winter- although I know, of course, that even if you are, you can't spare any time to

-2-
I hope that you are coming along nicely with the building of the little house and that you are going to have a most pleasant summer.
With kindest regards,
Very sincerely yours,
Burton Emmett
Mr. Sherwood Anderson,
Trout Dale,
Va.
In order that you may know the worst about me, I am enclosing my card. I know your great fondness (?) for advertising agencies. But dont judge all of us by your Chicago former employer, whoever he was. I worked for Mr. Lasker for two years (in New York office, but he spent half his time here) myself- about 1910.
